{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516612"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:44:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:44:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12668"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12668"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.2,0.32,0.18,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5144"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116412"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5144"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12668"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98411"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"96"},{"type":"tags","id":"493"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8668"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8677"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11008"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11796"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47869"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49065"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49954"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116412"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old man is admitted to the intensive care unit for diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) monitoring after he was found unconscious at home. He has a history of total hip replacement, COPD and type 1 diabetes mellitus managed with insulin. The DKA protocol was initiated, including correcting his hyperglycaemia, ketosis, acidaemia and dehydration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn day 2 of admission, the patient notes a one-hour history of mild chest pain, and palpitations. His 12 lead ECG showed the below changes (image). His admission ECG and ongoing telemetry prior to this episode was normal and he has not previously experience palpitations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient is lying in bed, he appears diaphoretic but otherwise well. His blood pressure is 102/84 mmHg, temperature 37.2\u00b0C, respiratory rate 20/min, heart rate 150bpm (regular), and SpO2 of 92%. His heart sounds are dual with no murmur and his chest is clear. His jugular venous pressure is mildly elevated and he has moist mucous membranes. He reports ongoing unpleasant palpitations and lightheadedness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the next most appropriate step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV metoprolol","Elective DC cardioversion","IV adenosine","IV amiodarone","PO apixaban"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has developed a new 2:1 atrial flutter, characterised by a ventricular rate of ~150/min and a saw-tooth pattern of atrial waves. The acute treatment of atrial flutter for haemodynamically stable patients can be divided into rhythm and rate control strategies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor effective rate control, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta blockers\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g. metoprolol) or non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers (e.g. diltiazem, verapamil) can be used. However, due to this patient\u0027s past history of COPD, beta blockers should be avoided due to the risk of bronchospasm. Furthermore, both IV beta-blockers and IV calcium channel blockers can worsen hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElective DC cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E is the most correct answer, given the patient has an acute (\u0026lt;12 hour) onset of atrial flutter. According to \u003Cem\u003E2015 ACC/AHA/HRS guideline for the management of adult patients with supraventricular tachycardia\u003C/em\u003E, \u0022elective synchronized cardioversion is indicated in stable patients with well-tolerated atrial flutter when a rhythm-control strategy is being pursued\u0022. Moreover, while the patient is currently haemodynamically stable, he is borderline hypotensive - increasing the validity of cardioversion (rather than rate-control).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV adenosine\u003C/strong\u003E induces a temporary AV block, which can be used to treat supraventricular tachycardias (e.g. AVNRT) and may unmask atrial flutter, where the diagnosis is uncertain. Of note, adenosine can reveal atrial flutter, but it does not treat/revert it. However, given the presence of saw-tooth waves in the ECG, the rate of 150bpm (highly indicative of a 2:1 block of atrial flutter), and the ECG performed post Valsalva manoeuvre, it is unlikely to be SVT, and thus this is not the next best step in management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV amiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E is an anti-arrhythmic agent that is commonly used for wide-complex tachycardias, and can be used for pharmacological cardioversion in atrial fibrillation and flutter. However, it is not recommended as it has a low efficacy, and there are more efficacious treatments, such as DC cardioversion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPO apixaban\u003C/strong\u003E, or another DOAC for at least 3 weeks duration would be indicated for elective DC cardioversion if the onset was \u0026gt;48 hours ago (or of unknown duration), particularly if there are other CHADS-VA criteria present. It is also commonly used in atrial fibrillation or flutter to prevent thromboembolic complications. However, while this patient would likely require a direct-acting oral anticoagulant (DOAC) on discharge (or after acute management), due to the acute onset of the patient\u0027s atrial flutter, it would not be the next most appropriate step in management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In haemodynamically stable patient with atrial flutter, DC electrocardioversion is the most effective treatment","Rate control strategies, such as IV beta blockers, may be useful in the acute setting of atrial flutter (e.g. before cardioversion)"],"references":["Page RL, Joglar JA, Caldwell MA, Calkins H, Conti JB, Deal BJ, et al. 2015 ACC/AHA/HRS guideline for the management of adult patients with supraventricular tachycardia: a report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Practice Guidelines and the Heart Rhythm Society. Circulation [Internet]. 2016 Apr 5 [cited 2023 July 1];133(14):e506-74. Available from: https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIR.0000000000000311 doi: 10.1161/CIR.0000000000000311","Stiell IG, de Wit K, Scheuermeyer FX, Vadeboncoeur A, Angaran P, Eagles D, Graham ID, Atzema CL, Archambault PM, Tebbenham T, McRae AD, Cheung WJ, Parkash R, Deyell MW, Baril G, Mann R, Sahsi R, Upadhye S, Brown E, Brinkhurst J, Chabot C, Skanes A. 2021 CAEP Acute Atrial Fibrillation/Flutter Best Practices Checklist. CJEM. 2021 Sep;23(5):604-610. doi: 10.1007/s43678-021-00167-y."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98411"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12668"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20676"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20676"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"i